---
import Doc from '../../layouts/Doc.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
import CommandPager from '../../components/CommandPager.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';

const title = 'scope';
const description =
  'Scope rules to file patterns so the right context loads in the right files. Frontend rules in frontend files. SQL rules in migrations. Nothing global unless it really is global.';
---

<Doc title={title} description={description} section="commands" eyebrow="Command">
  <p class="doc-lede">
    A single <code>CLAUDE.md</code> is fine for a single-stack repo. The moment
    you have a frontend and a backend, or an app and infra, or three
    languages, scoped rules become essential. Otherwise the agent sees your
    SQL conventions while editing a React component and gets distracted.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this command exists</h2>
  <p>
    The model has a finite attention budget. Every rule it reads is a token of
    that budget. When unrelated rules fire on the file the agent is editing,
    two things happen: it costs more, and the agent picks worse.
  </p>
  <p>
    <code>scope</code> moves rules to where they belong. Frontend conventions
    apply to <code>src/components/**/*.tsx</code>. SQL conventions apply to
    <code>db/migrations/**/*.sql</code>. Infra conventions apply to
    <code>terraform/**</code>. The top-level file shrinks to truly global
    rules — usually three or four — and the per-area files are short, opinionated
    and exactly what the agent needs in that location.
  </p>

  <Callout label="Read first" tone="ember">
    <p>
      The motivation is the
      <a href={url('foundation/anti-patterns/')}>"rules that fire everywhere"
      anti-pattern</a> (#6) and the
      <a href={url('foundation/good-practices/')}>scoped-rules good practice</a>
      (#8). The
      <a href={url('blueprint/#contextops')}>2026 Blueprint</a> identifies this
      as a standard 2026 pattern across Cursor, Copilot, and Claude Code.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>When to reach for it</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Multi-stack repo: frontend + backend, app + infra, multiple languages.</li>
    <li>Monorepo with several packages of distinct character.</li>
    <li>
      Rules keep firing where they should not. The agent applies frontend
      conventions to a Python script.
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>CLAUDE.md</code> has crept past 200 lines because it is trying to
      cover every area at once.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What it produces</h2>
  <p>Per-harness, one file per area:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Cursor</strong>: <code>.cursor/rules/&lt;area&gt;.mdc</code>
      with a <code>globs</code> frontmatter list. The cleanest scoping mechanism.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Copilot</strong>:
      <code>.github/instructions/&lt;area&gt;.instructions.md</code> with
      <code>applyTo</code> frontmatter.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Claude Code / Codex / generic</strong>: nested
      <code>CLAUDE.md</code> or <code>AGENTS.md</code> files at directory
      boundaries. The nested location <em>is</em> the scoping.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The top-level file is cleaned up at the same time. Rules duplicated in
    scoped files are removed or replaced with a pointer. The top-level file
    gets <em>shorter</em>, not longer.
  </p>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Map the repo.</strong> Globs top-level directories with source
      code. Notes primary languages and conventions that look different from
      the rest of the repo.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Ask which areas need their own rules.</strong> Multi-select,
      with detected candidates pre-listed: <code>src/components/</code>,
      <code>src/api/</code>, <code>db/migrations/</code>, <code>infra/</code>,
      <code>scripts/</code>, <code>tests/</code>. Plus which harnesses to
      target.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>For each area, gather rules.</strong> Reads a sample of files in
      the area, proposes 3–5 conventions with Preferred / Avoid pairs, asks
      you to confirm or edit.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Write the scoped files.</strong> Same body, different wrappers
      per harness.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Reconcile with the top-level file.</strong> Rules now in scoped
      files are removed or pointered. The top-level file gets leaner.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Verify.</strong> Pick one file in each newly-scoped area and
      check the right rules apply.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <Callout label="The quality bar" tone="mute">
    <p>
      Every scoped file has 3 to 6 rules. Not 1, not 15. Globs are accurate
      (test by listing matching files). The top-level file is leaner after
      this command than before. Every rule has a Preferred / Avoid pair or a
      verification command attached.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>Failure modes the command guards against</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Same rule in two scopes.</strong> If it applies to both
      frontend and backend, it is global. Put it at the top, not in both.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Glob too broad.</strong> <code>src/**/*</code> is not a scope;
      it is the whole project. Use it only if the rule really is universal.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Glob too narrow.</strong> A single file does not need its own
      scope. Inline-comment it instead.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Forgetting to clean up the top-level file.</strong> Scoping
      without removing duplicates just adds more files for the agent to read.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Related ideas</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/anti-patterns/')}>Anti-patterns</a> #6 — rules
      that fire everywhere.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/good-practices/')}>Good practices</a> #8 —
      scoped rules.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/harness-reference/')}>Harness reference</a> —
      Cursor frontmatter, Copilot <code>applyTo</code>, nested files for
      Claude Code.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('blueprint/#contextops')}>2026 Blueprint — scoped rules and
      context-modular patterns</a>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <CommandPager slug="scope" />
</Doc>
